title: Want To Buy:  NC star ak-47 top cover rail mount
postcontent:
So i bet a lot of people are looking for a rail solution for their AK-47 or AK-74. This rail system by NC Star is a decent and cheap alternative to a rail mount like Parabellum Armament's $130 rail, http://www.aimsurplus.com/product.aspx?item=XPAAKARSG3&name=Parabellum+Armament+AK+Adaptive+Rail+System&groupid=64
Personally I say send the extra 100 bucks. Its worth it. the NC Star mount is attached to the topcover and doesn't have the best consistency. And if you are trying to mount any scope larger than a 40mm then goodluck because it will not fit with original mounting equipment. The scope hits the first ironsite. 
The nice thing about the NCstar topcover is that you can still use the ironsights, sometimes even with a scope mounted. The parabellum mount replaces the rear iron sight. 
In the end, the NCstar mounting solution isn't ideal for the AK. Its not a consistent rail. If you are just using a reddot then go ahead. but anything else, spend the extra money and save yourself the headache.

Vest is used (worn but not shot) but good condition. There is some normal wear and tear on the carrier, but the Kevlar inserts are in great shape. The tag on the carrier says it is size 34 long, but the elastic Velcro straps make it adaptable to almost anyone. I wear a size 40 jacket and this fits me fine. The front plate of the vest has a pocket for a trauma plate insert, and a 10% reduction trauma pad is included. 

The Kevlar inserts state that they are Class IIIA, .208 inches thick and are designed to stop a 9mm bullet traveling at 1718 fps and a .44 mag traveling at 1616 fps. 

This vest retails new from $500 (but out of stock at that price) to $750 (in stock, plus shipping) online, and will stop a bullet the same way it did when it left the factory. The vest is thin enough to wear under clothing an go unnoticed and is about as comfortable as ballistic vests get.

Not to be confused with Medium ALICE Packs commonly found on the Internet, these packs are larger, with three main outside pouches and three smaller pouches above that are perfect for holding ammo magazines, radios and other small gear. Inside the top flap is a map pocket. Inside the pack is a large main compartment separated by a smaller compartment with a strap closure. These rugged, military-grade packs are made of water-repellent nylon and have snap-closure pouches, drawstring closures and ALICE webbing on the sides for attaching gear to the outside of the pack. Don't settle for a cheaply-made imitation ALICE pack when you can have the real thing for less.

In addition to military uses, these packs are perfect for hunting, camping, hiking, paintball and more.

It is SN 2445750

Grips (brown plastic or bakelite) inside Left one is 22 with a 5 point star.

Slide, Left side: REMINGTON RAND SYRACUSE, N.Y.U.S.A. 
Top fwd of rear sight: P

Barrel Lug, Left side: P
Right side: HS

Frame, Left side: by mag release; P
Behind trigger; Idiot scratch and FJA
Front of trigger guard; 1

Right side: U.S. PROPERTY M1911 U.S.ARMY
NO 2445750

Top by disconnector; G

All these markings are consistent with RR made 1911A1s.

None of the other parts have any markings that I can see.

title: For Sale:  .256 Newton, First Series model 1916
postcontent:
I bought the rifle a while ago as one of my projects. However, I am getting married and sadly I need to sell some projects collecting dust.

Newton Arms Co. First Series model 1916 in .256 Newton. Serial# 2419, serials match on bolt handle, bolt sleeve, floorplate, trigger guard, action bottom & stock channel. There were approximately 3900 first models manufactured with 62% being the .256 Newton. This rifle may have been one of the final First Series rifles manufactured in Buffalo. The barrel is marked with "Newton Arms Co., INC." "BUFFALO, N.Y." and "256 NEWTON".

The rifle has factory double set triggers, easy take-down floorplate, three position safety, multiple-lug bolt, all work well. It has been heavily used, but is in overall sound condition. The stock is solid with minor scrapes & dents. It does not have any cracks or repairs. The checkering is there, but the points are pretty flat & needs to be re-checkered. I would say the bluing is about 50% but there is no pitting anywhere. It is missing original iron sights & steel buttplate. There has been some filing on the rear bridge of the action. Hi Point firearms get a lot of grief, but they carry a lifetime warranty that transfers from owner to owner.
